VS Code&#39;s [syntax color themes](https://code.visualstudio.com/api/language-extensions/syntax-highlight-guide) can specify a `fontStyle` in addition to the color of syntax scopes. To make text italic, you&#39;d want to set `&quot;fontStyle&quot;: &quot;italic&quot;`

This example [`editor.tokenColorCustomizations` setting](https://code.visualstudio.com/api/extension-guides/color-theme#syntax-colors) uses `fontStyle` to make some html attributes italic:

```json
&quot;editor.tokenColorCustomizations&quot;: {
	&quot;textMateRules&quot;: [
		{
			&quot;scope&quot;: &quot;entity.other.attribute-name&quot;,
			&quot;settings&quot;: {
				&quot;fontStyle&quot;: &quot;italic&quot;
			}
		}
	]
}
```


Here&#39;s an [example of how to set `fontStyle` in an actual color theme](https://github.com/microsoft/vscode/blob/700780d927135cd78c1c653da63b8fd896c72bee/extensions/theme-abyss/themes/abyss-color-theme.json#L81).

`entity.other.attribute-name` is only an example scope. You may need to tweak the scope or style multiple scopes based on your specific needs
